# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transistor-scaling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] In semiconductor electronics, **Dennard scaling**, also known as **MOSFET scaling**, is a scaling law which states roughly that, as transistors get smaller, their power density stays constant, so that the power use stays in proportion with area; both voltage and current scale (downward) with length.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The law, originally formulated for MOSFETs, is based on a 1974 paper co-authored by Robert H.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] In fixed voltage scaling, the supply voltage $V_{\text{DD}}$ is held constant (at ~5 V) instead of scaling like ⁠ $V_{\text{DD}}\propto S^{-1}$ ⁠.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] This results in different scaling exponents.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The clock frequency grows faster, at $S^{2}$ instead of $S^{1}$ , but at the price of rapidly increasing power density ⁠ $PD\propto S^{3}$ ⁠.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Fixed voltage scaling was the common scaling regime which ended around 2005 at the "power wall", when it was too difficult to keep the chip cool.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Furthermore, at constant supply voltage, the field grows like ⁠ $S^{1}$ ⁠, and the off-current grows *exponentially* with the field, resulting in high static power consumption since the 90 nm node.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Power consumption of an individual transistor decreases by 51%, because active power is CV2f.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] As a result, power consumption per unit area remains the same for every technology generation.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Alternatively, with every generation the number of transistors in a chip can be doubled with no change in power consumption.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Moore's law says that the number of transistors on a microchip doubles approximately every two years.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Combined with Dennard scaling, this means that performance per joule grows even faster, doubling about every 18 months (1.5 years).
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] This trend is sometimes referred to as Koomey's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The rate of doubling was originally suggested by Koomey to be 1.57 years, but more recent estimates suggest this is slowing.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The dynamic (switching) power consumption of CMOS circuits is proportional to frequency.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Historically, the transistor power reduction afforded by Dennard scaling allowed manufacturers to drastically raise clock frequencies from one generation to the next without significantly increasing overall circuit power consumption.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] However, since around 2005–2007 Dennard scaling appears to have broken down.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Specifically, leakage current and threshold voltage do not scale with size, and so the power density increases with scaling.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] This eventually led to a power density that is too high.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] This is the "power wall", which caused Intel to cancel Tejas and Jayhawk in 2004.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] As of 2016, transistor counts in integrated circuits are still growing, but the resulting improvements in performance are more gradual than the speed-ups resulting from significant frequency increases.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The primary reason cited for the breakdown is that at small sizes, current leakage poses greater challenges and also causes the chip to heat up, which creates a threat of thermal runaway and therefore further increases energy costs.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] Since 2005, the clock frequency has stagnated at 4-6 GHz, and the power consumption per CPU at 100 W TDP.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The breakdown of Dennard scaling and resulting inability to increase clock frequencies significantly has caused most CPU manufacturers to focus on multicore processors as an alternative way to improve performance.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] An increased core count benefits many (though by no means all – see Amdahl's law) workloads, but the increase in active switching elements from having multiple cores still results in increased overall power consumption and thus worsens CPU power dissipation issues.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The end result is that only some fraction of an integrated circuit can actually be active at any given point in time without violating power constraints.
[src:transistor-scaling/dennard-scaling] The remaining (inactive) area is referred to as dark silicon.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] The term **die shrink** (sometimes **optical shrink** or **process shrink**) refers to the scaling of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] The act of shrinking a die creates a somewhat identical circuit using a more advanced fabrication process, usually involving an advance of lithographic nodes.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] This reduces overall costs for a chip company, as the absence of major architectural changes to the processor lowers research and development costs while at the same time allowing more processor dies to be manufactured on the same piece of silicon wafer, resulting in less cost per product sold.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] Die shrinks are the key to lower prices and higher performance at semiconductor companies such as Samsung, Intel, TSMC, and SK Hynix, and fabless manufacturers such as AMD (including the former ATI), NVIDIA and MediaTek.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] In January 2010, Intel released Clarkdale Core i5 and Core i7 processors fabricated with a 32 nm process, down from a previous 45 nm process used in older iterations of the Nehalem processor microarchitecture.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] Intel, in particular, formerly focused on leveraging die shrinks to improve product performance at a regular cadence through its Tick–Tock model.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] In this business model, every new microarchitecture (tock) is followed by a die shrink (tick) to improve performance with the same microarchitecture.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] Since the cost to fabricate a 200-mm or 300-mm silicon wafer is proportional to the number of fabrication steps and not proportional to the number of chips on the wafer, die shrinks cram more chips onto each wafer, resulting in lowered manufacturing costs per chip.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] In CPU fabrication, a die shrink always involves an advance to a lithographic node as defined by ITRS (see list).
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] For GPU and SoC manufacturing, the die shrink often involves shrinking the die on a node not defined by the ITRS, for instance, the 150 nm, 110 nm, 80 nm, 55 nm, 20 nm and more currently 4 nm nodes, sometimes referred to as "half-nodes".
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] This is a stopgap between two ITRS-defined lithographic nodes (thus called a "half-node shrink") before further shrink to the lower ITRS-defined nodes occurs, which helps save additional R&D cost.
[src:transistor-scaling/die-shrink] The choice to perform die shrinks to either full nodes or half-nodes rests with the foundry and not the integrated circuit designer.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A **multigate device**, **multi-gate MOSFET** or **multi-gate field-effect transistor** (**MuGFET**) refers to a metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET) that has more than one gate on a single transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The multiple gates may be controlled by a single gate electrode, wherein the multiple gate surfaces act electrically as a single gate, or by independent gate electrodes.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A multigate device employing independent gate electrodes is sometimes called a **multiple-independent-gate field-effect transistor** (**MIGFET**).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The most widely used multi-gate devices are the FinFET (fin field-effect transistor) and the GAAFET (gate-all-around field-effect transistor), which are non-planar transistors, or **3D transistors**.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The primary roadblock to widespread implementation is manufacturability, as both planar and non-planar designs present significant challenges, especially with respect to lithography and patterning.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Other complementary strategies for device scaling include channel strain engineering, silicon-on-insulator-based technologies, and high-κ/metal gate materials.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Dual-gate MOSFETs are commonly used in very high frequency (VHF) mixers and in sensitive VHF front-end amplifiers.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] They are available from manufacturers such as Motorola, NXP Semiconductors, and Hitachi.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Dozens of multigate transistor variants may be found in the literature.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In general, these variants may be differentiated and classified in terms of architecture (planar vs. non-planar design) and the number of channels/gates (2, 3, or 4).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In planar double-gate transistors the drain–source channel is sandwiched between two independently fabricated gate/gate-oxide stacks.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The primary challenge in fabricating such structures is achieving satisfactory self-alignment between the upper and lower gates.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] FinFET (fin field-effect transistor) is a type of non-planar transistor, or "3D" transistor (not to be confused with 3D microchips).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The FinFET is a variation on traditional MOSFETs distinguished by the presence of a thin silicon "fin" inversion channel on top of the substrate, allowing the gate to make two points of contact: the left and right sides of the fin.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The thickness of the fin (measured in the direction from source to drain) determines the effective channel length of the device.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The wrap-around gate structure provides a better electrical control over the channel and thus helps in reducing the leakage current and overcoming other short-channel effects.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The first FinFET transistor type was called a *depleted lean-channel transistor* or "DELTA" transistor, which was first fabricated by Hitachi Central Research Laboratory's Digh Hisamoto, Toru Kaga, Yoshifumi Kawamoto and Eiji Takeda in 1989.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In the late 1990s, Digh Hisamoto began collaborating with an international team of researchers on further developing DELTA technology, including TSMC's Chenming Hu and a UC Berkeley research team including Tsu-Jae King Liu, Jeffrey Bokor, Xuejue Huang, Leland Chang, Nick Lindert, S.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Ahmed, Cyrus Tabery, Yang-Kyu Choi, Pushkar Ranade, Sriram Balasubramanian, A.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 1998, the team developed the first N-channel FinFETs and successfully fabricated devices down to a 17 nm process.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The following year, they developed the first P-channel FinFETs.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] They coined the term "FinFET" (fin field-effect transistor) in a December 2000 paper.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In current usage the term FinFET has a less precise definition.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Among microprocessor manufacturers, AMD, IBM, and Freescale describe their double-gate development efforts as FinFET development, whereas Intel avoids using the term when describing their closely related tri-gate architecture.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In the technical literature, FinFET is used somewhat generically to describe any fin-based, multigate transistor architecture regardless of number of gates.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] It is common for a single FinFET transistor to contain several fins, arranged side by side and all covered by the same gate, that act electrically as one, to increase drive strength and performance.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The gate may also cover the entirety of the fin(s).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A 25 nm transistor operating on just 0.7 volt was demonstrated in December 2002 by TSMC (Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The "Omega FinFET" design is named after the similarity between the Greek letter omega (Ω) and the shape in which the gate wraps around the source/drain structure.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] It has a gate delay of just 0.39 picosecond (ps) for the N-type transistor and 0.88 ps for the P-type.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 2004, Samsung Electronics demonstrated a "Bulk FinFET" design, which made it possible to mass-produce FinFET devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] They demonstrated dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) manufactured with a 90 nm Bulk FinFET process.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 2006, a team of Korean researchers from the Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (KAIST) and the National Nano Fab Center developed a 3 nm transistor, the world's smallest nanoelectronic device, based on FinFET technology.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 2011, Rice University researchers Masoud Rostami and Kartik Mohanram demonstrated that FINFETs can have two electrically independent gates, which gives circuit designers more flexibility to design with efficient, low-power gates.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 2012, Intel started using FinFETs for its future commercial devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In September 2012, GlobalFoundries announced plans to offer a 14-nanometer process technology featuring FinFET three-dimensional transistors in 2014.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The next month, the rival company TSMC announced start early or "risk" production of 16 nm FinFETs in November 2013.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] AMD released GPUs using their Polaris chip architecture and made on 14 nm FinFET in June 2016.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The company has tried to produce a design to provide a "generational jump in power efficiency" while also offering stable frame rates for graphics, gaming, virtual reality, and multimedia applications.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In March 2017, Samsung and eSilicon announced the tapeout for production of a 14 nm FinFET ASIC in a 2.5D package.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A **tri-gate** transistor, also known as a triple-gate transistor, is a type of MOSFET with a gate on three of its sides.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A triple-gate transistor was first demonstrated in 1987, by a Toshiba research team including K.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] They realized that the fully depleted (FD) body of a narrow bulk Si-based transistor helped improve switching due to a reduced body-bias effect.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 1992, a triple-gate MOSFET was demonstrated by IBM researcher Hon-Sum Wong.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Intel announced this technology in September 2002.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Intel announced "triple-gate transistors" which maximize "transistor switching performance and decreases power-wasting leakage".
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A year later, in September 2003, AMD announced that it was working on similar technology at the International Conference on Solid State Devices and Materials.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] No further announcements of this technology were made until Intel's announcement in May 2011, although it was stated at IDF 2011, that they demonstrated a working SRAM chip based on this technology at IDF 2009.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] On April 23, 2012, Intel released a new line of CPUs, termed Ivy Bridge, which feature tri-gate transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Intel has been working on its tri-gate architecture since 2002, but it took until 2011 to work out mass-production issues.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The new style of transistor was described on May 4, 2011, in San Francisco.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] It was announced that Intel's factories were expected to make upgrades over 2011 and 2012 to be able to manufacture the Ivy Bridge CPUs.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] It was announced that the new transistors would also be used in Intel's Atom chips for low-powered devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Tri-gate fabrication was used by Intel for the non-planar transistor architecture used in Ivy Bridge, Haswell and Skylake processors.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] These transistors employ a single gate stacked on top of two vertical gates (a single gate wrapped over three sides of the channel), allowing essentially three times the surface area for electrons to travel.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Intel reports that their tri-gate transistors reduce leakage and consume far less power than previous transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] This allows up to 37% higher speed or a power consumption at under 50% of the previous type of transistors used by Intel.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The term *tri-gate* is sometimes used generically to denote any multigate FET with three effective gates or channels.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] GAAFET, also known as a surrounding-gate transistor (SGT), is similar in concept to a FinFET except that the gate material surrounds the channel region on all sides.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Depending on design, gate-all-around FETs can have two or four effective gates.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Gate-all-around FETs have been successfully characterized both theoretically and experimentally.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] They have also been successfully etched onto nanowires of InGaAs, which have a higher electron mobility than silicon.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A gate-all-around (GAA) MOSFET was first demonstrated in 1988, by a Toshiba research team including Fujio Masuoka, Hiroshi Takato, and Kazumasa Sunouchi, who demonstrated a vertical nanowire GAAFET which they called a "surrounding gate transistor" (SGT).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Masuoka, best known as the inventor of flash memory, later left Toshiba and founded Unisantis Electronics in 2004 to research surrounding-gate technology along with Tohoku University.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In 2006, a team of Korean researchers from the Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (KAIST) and the National Nano Fab Center developed a 3 nm transistor, the world's smallest nanoelectronic device, based on gate-all-around (GAA) FinFET technology.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] GAAFET transistors may make use of high-k/metal gate materials.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] GAAFETs with up to 7 nanosheets have been demonstrated which allow for improved performance and/or reduced device footprint.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The widths of the nanosheets in GAAFETs is controllable which more easily allows for the adjustment of device characteristics.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] As of 2020, Samsung and Intel have announced plans to mass produce GAAFET transistors (specifically MBCFET transistors) while TSMC has announced that they will continue to use FinFETs in their 3 nm node, despite TSMC developing GAAFET transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] A multi-bridge channel FET (MBCFET) is similar to a GAAFET except for the use of nanosheets instead of nanowires.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] MBCFET is a word mark (trademark) registered in the U.S. to Samsung Electronics.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Samsung plans on mass producing MBCFET transistors at the 3 nm node for its foundry customers.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Intel is also developing RibbonFET, a variation of MBCFET "nanoribbon" transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Unlike FinFETs, both the width and the number of the sheets can be varied to adjust drive strength or the amount of current the transistor can drive at a given voltage.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The sheets often vary from 8 to 50 nanometers in width.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The width of the nanosheets is known as Weff, or effective width.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Planar transistors have been the core of integrated circuits for several decades, during which the size of the individual transistors has steadily decreased.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] As the size decreases, planar transistors increasingly suffer from the undesirable short-channel effect, especially "off-state" leakage current, which increases the idle power required by the device.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] In a multigate device, the channel is surrounded by several gates on multiple surfaces.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Thus it provides better electrical control over the channel, allowing more effective suppression of "off-state" leakage current.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Multiple gates also allow enhanced current in the "on" state, also known as drive current.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Multigate transistors also provide a better analog performance due to a higher intrinsic gain and lower channel length modulation.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] These advantages translate to lower power consumption and enhanced device performance.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Nonplanar devices are also more compact than conventional planar transistors, enabling higher transistor density which translates to smaller overall microelectronics.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] BSIMCMG106.0.0, officially released on March 1, 2012 by UC Berkeley BSIM Group, is the first standard model for FinFETs.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Physical surface-potential-based formulations are derived for both intrinsic and extrinsic models with finite body doping.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The surface potentials at the source and drain ends are solved analytically with poly-depletion and quantum mechanical effects.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The effect of finite body doping is captured through a perturbation approach.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The analytic surface potential solution agrees closely with the 2-D device simulation results.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] If the channel doping concentration is low enough to be neglected, computational efficiency can be further improved by a setting a specific flag (COREMOD = 1).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] All of the important multi-gate (MG) transistor behavior is captured by this model.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Volume inversion is included in the solution of Poisson's equation, hence the subsequent I–V formulation automatically captures the volume-inversion effect.
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] Analysis of electrostatic potential in the body of MG MOSFETs provided a model equation for short-channel effects (SCE).
[src:transistor-scaling/gate-all-around] The extra electrostatic control from the end gates (top/bottom gates) (triple or quadruple-gate) is also captured in the short-channel model.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In 1975, looking forward to the next decade, he revised the forecast to doubling every two years, a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 41%.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore's empirical evidence did not imply that the historical trend would continue; nevertheless, his prediction has held since 1975 and has since become known as a *law*.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore's prediction has been used in the semiconductor industry to guide long-term planning and to set targets for research and development (R&D).
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Advancements in digital electronics, such as the reduction in quality-adjusted prices of microprocessors, the increase in memory capacity (RAM and flash), the improvement of sensors, and even the number and size of pixels in digital cameras, are strongly linked to Moore's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] These ongoing changes in digital electronics have been a driving force of technological and social change, productivity, and economic growth.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Industry experts have not reached a consensus on exactly when Moore's law will cease to apply.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Microprocessor architects report that semiconductor advancement has slowed industry-wide since around 2010, slightly below the pace predicted by Moore's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In September 2022, Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang considered Moore's law dead, while Intel's then CEO Pat Gelsinger had the opposite view.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In 1959, Douglas Engelbart studied the projected downscaling of integrated circuit (IC) size, publishing his results in the article "Microelectronics, and the Art of Similitude".
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Engelbart presented his findings at the 1960 International Solid-State Circuits Conference, where Moore was present in the audience.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] His response was a brief article entitled "Cramming more components onto integrated circuits".
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Within his editorial, he speculated that by 1975 it would be possible to contain as many as 65000 components on a single quarter-square-inch (~ 1.6 cm2) semiconductor.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore posited a log–linear relationship between device complexity (higher circuit density at reduced cost) and time.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In a 2015 interview, Moore noted of the 1965 article: "...
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] I just did a wild extrapolation saying it's going to continue to double every year for the next 10 years." One historian of the law cites Stigler's law of eponymy, to introduce the fact that the regular doubling of components was known to many working in the field.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Dennard at IBM recognized the rapid MOSFET scaling technology and formulated what became known as Dennard scaling, which describes that as MOS transistors get smaller, their power density stays constant such that the power use remains in proportion with area.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Evidence from the semiconductor industry shows that this inverse relationship between power density and areal density broke down in the mid-2000s.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] At the 1975 IEEE International Electron Devices Meeting, Moore revised his forecast rate, predicting semiconductor complexity would continue to double annually until about 1980, after which it would decrease to a rate of doubling approximately every two years.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Shortly after 1975, Caltech professor Carver Mead popularized the term *Moore's law*.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore's law eventually came to be widely accepted as a goal for the semiconductor industry, and it was cited by competitive semiconductor manufacturers as they strove to increase processing power.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore viewed his eponymous law as surprising and optimistic: "Moore's law is a violation of Murphy's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Everything gets better and better." The observation was even seen as a self-fulfilling prophecy.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The doubling period is often misquoted as 18 months because of a separate prediction by Moore's colleague, Intel executive David House.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In 1975, House noted that Moore's revised law of doubling transistor count every 2 years in turn implied that computer chip performance would roughly double every 18 months, with no increase in power consumption.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Mathematically, Moore's law predicted that transistor count would double every 2 years due to shrinking transistor dimensions and other improvements.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As a consequence of shrinking dimensions, Dennard scaling predicted that power consumption per unit area would remain constant.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Combining these effects, David House deduced that computer chip performance would roughly double every 18 months.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Also due to Dennard scaling, this increased performance would not be accompanied by increased power, i.e., the energy-efficiency of silicon-based computer chips roughly doubles every 18 months.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Koomey later showed that a similar rate of efficiency improvement predated silicon chips and Moore's law, for technologies such as vacuum tubes.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Microprocessor architects report that since around 2010, semiconductor advancement has slowed industry-wide below the pace predicted by Moore's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Brian Krzanich, the former CEO of Intel, cited Moore's 1975 revision as a precedent for the current deceleration, which results from technical challenges and is "a natural part of the history of Moore's law".
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The rate of improvement in physical dimensions known as Dennard scaling also ended in the mid-2000s.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As a result, much of the semiconductor industry has shifted its focus to the needs of major computing applications rather than semiconductor scaling.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Nevertheless, as of 2019, leading semiconductor manufacturers TSMC and Samsung Electronics claimed to keep pace with Moore's law with 10, 7, and 5 nm nodes in mass production.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As the cost of computer power to the consumer falls, the cost for producers to fulfill Moore's law follows an opposite trend: R&D, manufacturing, and test costs have increased steadily with each new generation of chips.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The cost of the tools, principally extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUVL), used to manufacture chips doubles every 4 years.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Rising manufacturing costs are an important consideration for the sustaining of Moore's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] This led to the formulation of Moore's second law, also called Rock's law (named after Arthur Rock), which is that the capital cost of a semiconductor fabrication plant also increases exponentially over time.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Numerous innovations by scientists and engineers have sustained Moore's law since the beginning of the IC era.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Some of the key innovations are listed below, as examples of breakthroughs that have advanced integrated circuit and semiconductor device fabrication technology, allowing transistor counts to grow by more than seven orders of magnitude in less than five decades.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Computer industry technology road maps predicted in 2001 that Moore's law would continue for several generations of semiconductor chips.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] One of the key technical challenges of engineering future nanoscale transistors is the design of gates.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As device dimensions shrink, controlling the current flow in the thin channel becomes more difficult.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Modern nanoscale transistors typically take the form of multi-gate MOSFETs, with the FinFET being the most common nanoscale transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The FinFET has gate dielectric on three sides of the channel.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In comparison, the gate-all-around MOSFET (GAAFET) structure has even better gate control.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Microprocessor architects report that semiconductor advancement has slowed industry-wide since around 2010, below the pace predicted by Moore's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Brian Krzanich, the former CEO of Intel, announced in 2015, "Our cadence today is closer to two and a half years than two." Intel stated in 2015 that improvements in MOSFET devices have slowed, starting at the 22 nm feature width around 2012, and continuing at 14 nm.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The physical limits to transistor scaling have been reached due to source-to-drain leakage, limited gate metals and limited options for channel material.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Other approaches are being investigated, which do not rely on physical scaling.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] These include the spin state of electron spintronics, tunnel junctions, and advanced confinement of channel materials via nano-wire geometry.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Spin-based logic and memory options are being developed actively in labs.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The vast majority of current transistors on integrated circuits are composed principally of doped silicon and its alloys.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As silicon is fabricated into single nanometer transistors, short-channel effects adversely changes desired material properties of silicon as a functional transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Below are several non-silicon substitutes in the fabrication of small nanometer transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] One proposed material is indium gallium arsenide, or InGaAs.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Compared to their silicon and germanium counterparts, InGaAs transistors are more promising for future high-speed, low-power logic applications.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Because of intrinsic characteristics of III–V compound semiconductors, quantum well and tunnel effect transistors based on InGaAs have been proposed as alternatives to more traditional MOSFET designs.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Biological computing research shows that biological material has superior information density and energy efficiency compared to silicon-based computing.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Various forms of graphene are being studied for graphene electronics, e.g., graphene nanoribbon transistors have shown promise since their appearance in publications in 2008.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] (Bulk graphene has a band gap of zero and thus cannot be used in transistors because of its constant conductivity, an inability to turn off.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The zigzag edges of the nanoribbons introduce localized energy states in the conduction and valence bands and thus a bandgap that enables switching when fabricated as a transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As an example, a typical GNR of width of 10 nm has a desirable bandgap energy of 0.4 eV.) More research will need to be performed, however, on sub-50 nm graphene layers, as its resistivity value increases and thus electron mobility decreases.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In April 2005, Gordon Moore stated in an interview that the projection cannot be sustained indefinitely: "It can't continue forever.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In 2016 the International Technology Roadmap for Semiconductors, after using Moore's Law to drive the industry since 1998, produced its final roadmap.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] It no longer centered its research and development plan on Moore's law.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Instead, it outlined what might be called the More than Moore strategy in which the needs of applications drive chip development, rather than a focus on semiconductor scaling.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Application drivers range from smartphones to AI to data centers.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] IEEE began a road-mapping initiative in 2016, Rebooting Computing, named the International Roadmap for Devices and Systems (IRDS).
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Some forecasters, including Gordon Moore, predicted between 2012–2016 that Moore's law would end by around 2025.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Although Moore's Law will reach a physical limit, some forecasters in 2019 and 2020 were optimistic about the continuation of technological progress in a variety of other areas, including new chip architectures, quantum computing, and AI and machine learning.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang declared Moore's law dead in 2022; several days later, Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger countered with the opposite claim.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Digital electronics have contributed to world economic growth in the late twentieth and early twenty-first centuries.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The primary driving force of economic growth is the growth of productivity, which Moore's law factors into.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore (1995) expected that "the rate of technological progress is going to be controlled from financial realities".
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The reverse could and did occur around the late-1990s, however, with economists reporting that "Productivity growth is the key economic indicator of innovation." Moore's law describes a driving force of technological and social change, productivity, and economic growth.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] An acceleration in the rate of semiconductor progress contributed to a surge in U.S. productivity growth, which reached 3.4% per year in 1997–2004, outpacing the 1.6% per year during both 1972–1996 and 2005–2013.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The primary negative implication of Moore's law is that it is associated with rapid obsolescence and accordingly high maintenance costs.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As technologies continue to rapidly improve, they render predecessor technologies obsolete.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In situations in which security and survivability of hardware or data are paramount, or in which resources are limited, rapid obsolescence often poses obstacles to smooth or continued operations.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Several measures of digital technology are improving at exponential rates related to Moore's law, including the size, cost, density, and speed of components.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore wrote only about the density of components, "a component being a transistor, resistor, diode or capacitor", at minimum cost.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] As more transistors are put on a chip, the cost to make each transistor decreases, but the chance that the chip will not work due to a defect increases.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In 1965, Moore examined the density of transistors at which cost is minimized, and observed that, as transistors were made smaller through advances in photolithography, this number would increase at "a rate of roughly a factor of two per year".
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The exponential processor transistor growth predicted by Moore does not always translate into exponentially greater practical CPU performance.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Since around 2005–2007, Dennard scaling has ended, so even though Moore's law continued after that, it has not yielded proportional dividends in improved performance.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The primary reason cited for the breakdown is that at small sizes, current leakage poses greater challenges, and also causes the chip to heat up, which creates a threat of thermal runaway and therefore, further increases energy costs.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The breakdown of Dennard scaling prompted a greater focus on multicore processors, but the gains offered by switching to more cores are lower than the gains that would be achieved had Dennard scaling continued.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] In another departure from Dennard scaling, Intel microprocessors adopted a non-planar tri-gate FinFET at 22 nm in 2012 that is faster and consumes less power than a conventional planar transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The rate of performance improvement for single-core microprocessors has slowed significantly.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Single-core performance was improving by 52% per year in 1986–2003 and 23% per year in 2003–2011, but slowed to just seven percent per year in 2011–2018.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] While quality-adjusted microprocessor price improvement continues, the rate of improvement likewise varies, and is not linear on a log scale.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Microprocessor price improvement accelerated during the late 1990s, reaching 60% per year (halving every nine months) versus the typical 30% improvement rate (halving every two years) during the years earlier and later.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Laptop microprocessors in particular improved 25–35% per year in 2004–2010, and slowed to 15–25% per year in 2010–2013.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] The number of transistors per chip cannot explain quality-adjusted microprocessor prices fully.
[src:transistor-scaling/moore-s-law] Moore's 1995 paper does not limit Moore's law to strict linearity or to transistor count, "The definition of 'Moore's Law' has come to refer to almost anything related to the semiconductor industry that on a semi-log plot approximates a straight line.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] The **transistor count** is the number of transistors in an electronic device (typically on a single substrate or silicon die).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] It is the most common measure of integrated circuit complexity (although the majority of transistors in modern microprocessors are contained in cache memories, which consist mostly of the same memory cell circuits replicated many times).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] The rate at which MOS transistor counts have increased generally follows Moore's law, which observes that transistor count doubles approximately every two years.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] However, being directly proportional to the area of a die, transistor count does not represent how advanced the corresponding manufacturing technology is.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] A better indication of this is transistor density which is the ratio of a device's transistor count to its die area.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] As of 2023, the highest transistor count in flash memory is Micron's 2 terabyte (3D-stacked) 16-die, 232-layer V-NAND flash memory chip, with 5.3 trillion floating-gate MOSFETs (3 bits per transistor).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] The highest transistor count in a single chip processor as of 2020 is that of the deep learning processor Wafer Scale Engine 2 by Cerebras.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] It has 2.6 trillion MOSFETs in 84 exposed fields (dies) on a wafer, manufactured using TSMC's 7 nm FinFET process.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] As of 2026, the GPU with the highest transistor count is Nvidia's Rubin accelerator, built on TSMC's custom N3P process node and totaling 336 billion MOSFETs.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] The highest transistor count in a consumer microprocessor as of March 2025 is 184 billion transistors, in Apple's ARM-based dual-die M3 Ultra SoC, which is fabricated using TSMC's 3 nm semiconductor manufacturing process.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] Early experimental solid-state computers had as few as 130 transistors but used large amounts of diode logic.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] The first carbon nanotube computer had 178 transistors and was a 1-bit one-instruction set computer, while a later one is 16-bit (its instruction set is 32-bit RISC-V though).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p01] Ionic transistor chips ("water-based" analog limited processor), have up to hundreds of such transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] A microprocessor incorporates the functions of a computer's central processing unit on a single integrated circuit.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] It is a multi-purpose, programmable device that accepts digital data as input, processes it according to instructions stored in its memory, and provides results as output.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The development of MOS integrated circuit technology in the 1960s led to the development of the first microprocessors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The 20-bit MP944, developed by Garrett AiResearch for the U.S.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] Navy's F-14 Tomcat fighter in 1970, is considered by its designer Ray Holt to be the first microprocessor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] It was a multi-chip microprocessor, fabricated on six MOS chips.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] However, it was classified by the Navy until 1998.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The 4-bit Intel 4004, released in 1971, was the first single-chip microprocessor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] Modern microprocessors typically include on-chip cache memories.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The number of transistors used for these cache memories typically far exceeds the number of transistors used to implement the logic of the microprocessor (that is, excluding the cache).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] For example, the last DEC Alpha chip uses 90% of its transistors for cache.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] A graphics processing unit (GPU) is a specialized electronic circuit designed to rapidly manipulate and alter memory to accelerate the building of images in a frame buffer intended for output to a display.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The designer refers to the technology company that designs the logic of the integrated circuit chip (such as Nvidia and AMD).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The manufacturer ("Fab.") refers to the semiconductor company that fabricates the chip using its semiconductor manufacturing process at a foundry (such as TSMC and Samsung Semiconductor).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The transistor count in a chip is dependent on a manufacturer's fabrication process, with smaller semiconductor nodes typically enabling higher transistor density and thus higher transistor counts.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The random-access memory (RAM) that comes with GPUs (such as VRAM, SGRAM or HBM) greatly increases the total transistor count, with the memory typically accounting for the majority of transistors in a graphics card.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] For example, Nvidia's Tesla P100 has 15 billion FinFETs (16 nm) in the GPU in addition to 16 GB of HBM2 memory, totaling about 150 billion MOSFETs on the graphics card.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] The following table does not include the memory.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p02] For memory transistor counts, see the *Memory* section below.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] A field-programmable gate array (FPGA) is an integrated circuit designed to be configured by a customer or a designer after manufacturing.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Semiconductor memory is an electronic data storage device, often used as computer memory, implemented on integrated circuits.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Nearly all semiconductor memories since the 1970s have used MOSFETs (MOS transistors), replacing earlier bipolar junction transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] There are two major types of semiconductor memory: random-access memory (RAM) and non-volatile memory (NVM).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] In turn, there are two major RAM types: dynamic random-access memory (DRAM) and static random-access memory (SRAM), as well as two major NVM types: flash memory and read-only memory (ROM).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Typical CMOS SRAM consists of six transistors per cell.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] For DRAM, 1T1C, which means one transistor and one capacitor structure, is common.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Capacitor charged or not is used to store 1 or 0.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] In flash memory, the data is stored in floating gates, and the resistance of the transistor is sensed to interpret the data stored.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Depending on how fine scale the resistance could be separated, one transistor could store up to three bits, meaning eight distinctive levels of resistance possible per transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] However, a finer scale comes with the cost of repeatability issues, and hence reliability.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Typically, low grade 2-bits MLC flash is used for flash drives, so a 16 GB flash drive contains roughly 64 billion transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] For SRAM chips, six-transistor cells (six transistors per bit) was the standard.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] DRAM chips during the early 1970s had three-transistor cells (three transistors per bit), before single-transistor cells (one transistor per bit) became standard since the era of 4 Kb DRAM in the mid-1970s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] In single-level flash memory, each cell contains one floating-gate MOSFET (one transistor per bit), whereas multi-level flash contains 2, 3 or 4 bits per transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Flash memory chips are commonly stacked up in layers, up to 128-layer in production, and 136-layer managed, and available in end-user devices up to 69-layer from manufacturers.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Before transistors were invented, relays were used in commercial tabulating machines and experimental early computers.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The world's first working programmable, fully automatic digital computer, the 1941 Z3 22-bit word length computer, had 2,600 relays, and operated at a clock frequency of about 4–5 Hz.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The 1940 Complex Number Computer had fewer than 500 relays, but it was not fully programmable.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The earliest practical computers used vacuum tubes and solid-state diode logic.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] ENIAC had 18,000 vacuum tubes, 7,200 crystal diodes, and 1,500 relays, with many of the vacuum tubes containing two triode elements.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The second generation of computers were transistor computers that featured boards filled with discrete transistors, solid-state diodes and magnetic memory cores.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The experimental 1953 48-bit Transistor Computer, developed at the University of Manchester, is widely believed to be the first transistor computer to come into operation anywhere in the world (the prototype had 92 point-contact transistors and 550 diodes).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] A later version the 1955 machine had a total of 250 junction transistors and 1,300 point-contact diodes.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The Computer also used a small number of tubes in its clock generator, so it was not the first *fully* transistorized.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The ETL Mark III, developed at the Electrotechnical Laboratory in 1956, may have been the first transistor-based electronic computer using the stored program method.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] It had about "130 point-contact transistors and about 1,800 germanium diodes were used for logic elements, and these were housed on 300 plug-in packages which could be slipped in and out." The 1958 decimal architecture IBM 7070 was the first transistor computer to be fully programmable.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] It had about 30,000 alloy-junction germanium transistors and 22,000 germanium diodes, on approximately 14,000 Standard Modular System (SMS) cards.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The 1959 MOBIDIC, short for "MOBIle DIgital Computer", at 12,000 pounds (6.0 short tons) mounted in the trailer of a semi-trailer truck, was a transistorized computer for battlefield data.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The third generation of computers used integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The 1962 15-bit Apollo Guidance Computer used "about 4,000 "Type-G" (3-input NOR gate) circuits" for about 12,000 transistors plus 32,000 resistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The IBM System/360, introduced 1964, used discrete transistors in hybrid circuit packs.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The 1965 12-bit PDP-8 CPU had 1409 discrete transistors and over 10,000 diodes, on many cards.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Later versions, starting with the 1968 PDP-8/I, used integrated circuits.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The PDP-8 was later reimplemented as a microprocessor as the Intersil 6100, see below.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The next generation of computers were the microcomputers, starting with the 1971 Intel 4004, which used MOS transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] These were used in home computers or personal computers (PCs).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] This list includes early transistorized computers (second generation) and IC-based computers (third generation) from the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Transistor count for generic logic functions is based on static CMOS implementation.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Historically, each processing element in earlier parallel systems—like all CPUs of that time—was a serial computer built out of multiple chips.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] As transistor counts per chip increases, each processing element could be built out of fewer chips, and then later each multi-core processor chip could contain more processing elements.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Goodyear MPP: (1983?) 8 pixel processors per chip, 3,000 to 8,000 transistors per chip.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Brunel University Scape (single-chip array-processing element): (1983) 256 pixel processors per chip, 120,000 to 140,000 transistors per chip.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] Cell Broadband Engine: (2006) with 9 cores per chip, had 234 million transistors per chip.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The transistor density is the number of transistors that are fabricated per unit area, typically measured in terms of the number of transistors per square millimeter (mm2).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] The transistor density usually correlates with the gate length of a semiconductor node (also known as a semiconductor manufacturing process), typically measured in nanometers (nm).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] In certain applications, the term **gate count** is preferred over the term transistor count.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-count-p03] It refers to the number of logic gates built with transistors and other electronic devices needed to implement a design.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A **transistor** is a semiconductor device used to amplify or switch electrical signals and power.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It is one of the basic building blocks of modern electronics.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It is composed of semiconductor material, usually with at least three terminals for connection to an electronic circuit.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A voltage or current applied to one pair of the transistor's terminals controls the current through another pair of terminals.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because the controlled (output) power can be higher than the controlling (input) power, a transistor can amplify a signal.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Some transistors are packaged individually, but many more in miniature form are found embedded in integrated circuits.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because transistors are the key active components in practically all modern electronics, they are considered one of the 20th century's greatest inventions.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Physicist Julius Edgar Lilienfeld proposed the concept of a field-effect transistor (FET) in 1925, but it was not possible to construct a working device at that time.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first working device was a point-contact transistor invented in 1947 by physicists John Bardeen, Walter Brattain, and William Shockley at Bell Labs who shared the 1956 Nobel Prize in Physics for their achievement.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The most widely used type of transistor, the metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET), was invented at Bell Labs between 1955 and 1960.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Transistors revolutionized the field of electronics and paved the way for smaller and cheaper radios, calculators, computers, and other electronic devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Most transistors are made from very pure silicon, and some from germanium, but certain other semiconductor materials are sometimes used.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A transistor may have only one kind of charge carrier in a field-effect transistor, or may have two kinds of charge carriers in bipolar junction transistor devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Compared with the vacuum tube, transistors are generally smaller and require less power to operate.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Certain vacuum tubes have advantages over transistors at very high operating frequencies or high operating voltages, such as traveling-wave tubes and gyrotrons.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Many types of transistors are made to standardized specifications by multiple manufacturers.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The thermionic triode, a vacuum tube invented in 1907, enabled amplified radio technology and long-distance telephony.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The triode, however, was a fragile device that consumed a substantial amount of power.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1909, physicist William Eccles discovered the crystal diode oscillator.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Physicist Julius Edgar Lilienfeld filed a patent for a field-effect transistor (FET) in Canada in 1925, intended as a solid-state replacement for the triode.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] He filed identical patents in the United States in 1926 and 1928.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] However, he did not publish any research articles about his devices nor did his patents cite any specific examples of a working prototype.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because the production of high-quality semiconductor materials was still decades away, Lilienfeld's solid-state amplifier ideas would not have found practical use in the 1920s and 1930s, even if such a device had been built.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1934, inventor Oskar Heil patented a similar device in Europe.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] independently invented a point-contact transistor in June 1948.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] From November 17 to December 23, 1947, John Bardeen and Walter Brattain at AT&T's Bell Labs in Murray Hill, New Jersey, performed experiments and observed that when two gold point contacts were applied to a crystal of germanium, a signal was produced with the output power greater than the input.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Solid State Physics Group leader William Shockley saw the potential in this, and over the next few months worked to greatly expand the knowledge of semiconductors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The term *transistor* was coined by John R.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Pierce as a contraction of the term *transresistance*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] According to Lillian Hoddeson and Vicki Daitch, Shockley proposed that Bell Labs' first patent for a transistor should be based on the field-effect and that he be named as the inventor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Having unearthed Lilienfeld's patents that went into obscurity years earlier, lawyers at Bell Labs advised against Shockley's proposal because the idea of a field-effect transistor that used an electric field as a *grid* was not new.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Instead, what Bardeen, Brattain, and Shockley invented in 1947 was the first point-contact transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] To acknowledge this accomplishment, Shockley, Bardeen and Brattain jointly received the 1956 Nobel Prize in Physics "for their researches on semiconductors and their discovery of the transistor effect".
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Shockley's team initially attempted to build a field-effect transistor (FET) by trying to modulate the conductivity of a semiconductor, but was unsuccessful, mainly due to problems with the surface states, the dangling bond, and the germanium and copper compound materials.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Trying to understand the mysterious reasons behind this failure led them instead to invent the bipolar point-contact and junction transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1948, the point-contact transistor was independently invented by physicists Herbert Mataré and Heinrich Welker while working at the *Compagnie des Freins et Signaux Westinghouse*, a Westinghouse subsidiary in Paris.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Mataré had previous experience in developing Crystal detectors from silicon and germanium in the German radar effort during World War II.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] With this knowledge, he began researching the phenomenon of *interference* in 1947.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] By June 1948, witnessing currents flowing through point-contacts, he produced consistent results using samples of germanium produced by Welker, similar to what Bardeen and Brattain had accomplished earlier in December 1947.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Realizing that Bell Labs' scientists had already invented the transistor, the company rushed to get its *transistron* into production for amplified use in France's telephone network, filing his first transistor patent application on August 13, 1948.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first bipolar junction transistors were invented by Bell Labs' William Shockley, who applied for patent (2,569,347) on June 26, 1948.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] On April 12, 1950, Bell Labs chemists Gordon Teal and Morgan Sparks successfully produced a working bipolar NPN junction amplifying germanium transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Bell announced the discovery of this new *sandwich* transistor in a press release on July 4, 1951.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first high-frequency transistor was the surface-barrier germanium transistor developed by Philco in 1953, capable of operating at frequencies up to 60 MHz.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] They were made by etching depressions into an n-type germanium base from both sides with jets of indium(III) sulfate until it was a few ten-thousandths of an inch thick.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Indium electroplated into the depressions formed the collector and emitter.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] AT&T first used transistors in telecommunications equipment in the No.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] 4A Toll Crossbar Switching System in 1953, for selecting trunk circuits from routing information encoded on translator cards.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Its predecessor, the Western Electric No.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] 3A phototransistor, read the mechanical encoding from punched metal cards.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first prototype pocket transistor radio was shown by INTERMETALL, a company founded by Herbert Mataré in 1952, at the *Internationale Funkausstellung Düsseldorf* from August 29 to September 6, 1953.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first production-model pocket transistor radio was the Regency TR-1, released in October 1954.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Produced as a joint venture between the Regency Division of Industrial Development Engineering Associates, I.D.E.A. and Texas Instruments of Dallas, Texas, the TR-1 was manufactured in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It was a near pocket-sized radio with four transistors and one germanium diode.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The industrial design was outsourced to the Chicago firm of Painter, Teague and Petertil.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It was initially released in one of six colours: black, ivory, mandarin red, cloud grey, mahogany and olive green.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first production all-transistor car radio was developed by Chrysler and Philco corporations and was announced in the April 28, 1955, edition of *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Chrysler made the Mopar model 914HR available as an option starting in fall 1955 for its new line of 1956 Chrysler and Imperial cars, which reached dealership showrooms on October 21, 1955.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The Sony TR-63, released in 1957, was the first mass-produced transistor radio, leading to the widespread adoption of transistor radios.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Seven million TR-63s were sold worldwide by the mid-1960s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Sony's success with transistor radios led to transistors replacing vacuum tubes as the dominant electronic technology in the late 1950s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first working silicon transistor was developed at Bell Labs on January 26, 1954, by Morris Tanenbaum.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first production commercial silicon transistor was announced by Texas Instruments in May 1954.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This was the work of Gordon Teal, an expert in growing crystals of high purity, who had previously worked at Bell Labs.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The basic principle of the field-effect transistor (FET) was first proposed by physicist Julius Edgar Lilienfeld when he filed a patent for a device similar to MESFET in 1926, and for an insulated-gate field-effect transistor in 1928.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The FET concept was later also theorized by engineer Oskar Heil in the 1930s and by William Shockley in the 1940s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1945, JFET was patented by Heinrich Welker.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Following Shockley's theoretical treatment on JFET in 1952, a working practical JFET was made in 1953 by George C.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1948, Bardeen and Brattain patented the progenitor of MOSFET at Bell Labs, an insulated-gate FET (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Bardeen's patent, and the concept of an inversion layer, forms the basis of CMOS and DRAM technology today.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In the early years of the semiconductor industry, companies focused on the junction transistor, a relatively bulky device that was difficult to mass-produce, limiting it to several specialized applications.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Field-effect transistors (FETs) were theorized as potential alternatives, but researchers could not get them to work properly, largely due to the surface state barrier that prevented the external electric field from penetrating the material.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1955, Carl Frosch and Lincoln Derick accidentally grew a layer of silicon dioxide over the silicon wafer, for which they observed surface passivation effects.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] By 1957 Frosch and Derick, using masking and predeposition, were able to manufacture silicon dioxide field-effect transistors; the first planar transistors, in which drain and source were adjacent at the same surface.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] They showed that silicon dioxide insulated and protected silicon wafers and prevented dopants from diffusing into the wafer.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Spitzer studied the mechanism of thermally grown oxides, fabricated a high-quality Si/SiO2 stack and published their results in 1960.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Following this research, Mohamed Atalla and Dawon Kahng proposed a silicon MOS transistor in 1959 and successfully demonstrated a working MOS device with their Bell Labs team in 1960.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Povilonis, who fabricated the device; M.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Ligenza, who developed the diffusion processes, and H.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] With its high scalability, much lower power consumption, and higher density than bipolar junction transistors, the MOSFET made it possible to build high-density integrated circuits, allowing the integration of more than 10,000 transistors in a single IC.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Bardeen and Brattain's 1948 inversion-layer concept forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The CMOS (complementary MOS) was invented by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first report of a floating-gate MOSFET was made by Dawon Kahng and Simon Sze in 1967.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In 1967, Bell Labs researchers Robert Kerwin, Donald Klein and John Sarace developed the self-aligned gate (silicon-gate) MOS transistor, which Fairchild Semiconductor researchers Federico Faggin and Tom Klein used to develop the first silicon-gate MOS integrated circuit.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A double-gate MOSFET was first demonstrated in 1984 by Electrotechnical Laboratory researchers Toshihiro Sekigawa and Yutaka Hayashi.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The FinFET (fin field-effect transistor), a type of 3D non-planar multi-gate MOSFET, originated from the research of Digh Hisamoto and his team at Hitachi Central Research Laboratory in 1989.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because transistors are the key active components in practically all modern electronics, many people consider them one of the 20th century's greatest inventions.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The 1947 invention of the first transistor at Bell Labs was named an IEEE Milestone in 2009.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Other Milestones include the inventions of the junction transistor in 1948 and the MOSFET in 1959.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The MOSFET is by far the most widely used transistor, in applications ranging from computers and electronics to communications technology such as smartphones.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It has been considered the most important transistor, possibly the most important invention in electronics, and the device that enabled modern electronics.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It has been the basis of modern digital electronics since the late 20th century, paving the way for the digital age.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The US Patent and Trademark Office calls it a "groundbreaking invention that transformed life and culture around the world".
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Its ability to be mass-produced by a highly automated process (semiconductor device fabrication), from relatively basic materials, allows astonishingly low per-transistor costs.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] MOSFETs are the most numerously produced artificial objects in history, with more than 13 sextillion manufactured by 2018.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A logic gate consists of up to about 20 transistors, whereas an advanced microprocessor, As of 2023, may contain as many as 92 billion transistors on a die, and double that 184 billion when dual die (and for exceptional chips, 2.6 trillion transistors, as of 2020).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Transistors are often organized into logic gates in microprocessors to perform computation.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The transistor's low cost, flexibility and reliability have made it ubiquitous.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Transistorized mechatronic circuits have replaced electromechanical devices in controlling appliances and machinery.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It is often easier and cheaper to use a standard microcontroller and write a computer program to carry out a control function than to design an equivalent mechanical system.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A transistor can use a small signal applied between one pair of its terminals to control a much larger signal at another pair of terminals, a property called gain.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It can produce a stronger output signal, a voltage or current, proportional to a weaker input signal, acting as an amplifier.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It can also be used as an electrically controlled switch, where the amount of current is determined by other circuit elements.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The top image in this section represents a typical bipolar transistor in a circuit.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A charge flows between emitter and collector terminals depending on the current in the base.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because the base and emitter connections behave like a semiconductor diode, a voltage drop develops between them.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The amount of this drop, determined by the transistor's material, is referred to as *V*BE.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Transistors are commonly used in digital circuits as electronic switches which can be either in an *on* or *off* state, both for high-power applications such as switched-mode power supplies and for low-power applications such as logic gates.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Important parameters for this application include the current switched, the voltage handled, and the switching speed, characterized by the rise and fall times.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In a switching circuit, the goal is to simulate, as near as possible, the ideal switch having the properties of an open circuit when off, the short circuit when on, and an instantaneous transition between the two states.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Parameters are chosen such that the *off* output is limited to leakage currents too small to affect connected circuitry, the resistance of the transistor in the *on* state is too small to affect circuitry, and the transition between the two states is fast enough not to have a detrimental effect.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In a grounded-emitter transistor circuit, such as the light-switch circuit shown, as the base voltage rises, the emitter and collector currents rise exponentially.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The collector voltage drops because of reduced resistance from the collector to the emitter.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] If the voltage difference between the collector and emitter were zero (or near zero), the collector current would be limited only by the load resistance (light bulb) and the supply voltage.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This is called *saturation* because the current is flowing from collector to emitter freely.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] When saturated, the switch is said to be *on*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The use of bipolar transistors for switching applications requires biasing the transistor so that it operates between its cut-off region in the off-state and the saturation region (*on*).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This requires sufficient base drive current.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] As the transistor provides current gain, it facilitates the switching of a relatively large current in the collector by a much smaller current into the base terminal.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The ratio of these currents varies depending on the type of transistor, and even for a particular type, varies depending on the collector current.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In the example of a light-switch circuit, as shown, the resistor is chosen to provide enough base current to ensure the transistor is saturated.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The base resistor value is calculated from the supply voltage, transistor C-E junction voltage drop, collector current, and amplification factor beta.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The common-emitter amplifier is designed so that a small change in voltage (*V*in) changes the small current through the base of the transistor whose current amplification combined with the properties of the circuit means that small swings in *V*in produce large changes in *V*out.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Various configurations of single transistor amplifiers are possible, with some providing current gain, some voltage gain, and some both.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] From mobile phones to televisions, vast numbers of products include amplifiers for sound reproduction, radio transmission, and signal processing.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The first discrete-transistor audio amplifiers barely supplied a few hundred milliwatts, but power and audio fidelity gradually increased as better transistors became available and amplifier architecture evolved.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Modern transistor audio amplifiers of up to a few hundred watts are common and relatively inexpensive.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Before transistors were developed, vacuum tubes (or in the UK *thermionic valves* or just *valves*) were the main active components in electronic equipment.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Hence, a particular transistor may be described as *silicon, surface-mount, BJT, NPN, low-power, high-frequency switch*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Convenient mnemonic to remember the type of transistor (represented by an electrical symbol) involves the direction of the arrow.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For the BJT, on an **n–p–n** transistor symbol, the arrow will "**N**ot **P**oint i**N"**.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] However, this does not apply to MOSFET-based transistor symbols as the arrow is typically reversed (i.e. the arrow for the n–p–n points inside).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The *field-effect transistor*, sometimes called a *unipolar transistor*, uses either electrons (in *n-channel FET*) or holes (in *p-channel FET*) for conduction.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The four terminals of the FET are named *source*, *gate*, *drain*, and *body* (*substrate*).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] On most FETs, the body is connected to the source inside the package, and this will be assumed for the following description.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In a FET, the drain-to-source current flows via a conducting channel that connects the *source* region to the *drain* region.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The conductivity is varied by the electric field that is produced when a voltage is applied between the gate and source terminals, hence the current flowing between the drain and source is controlled by the voltage applied between the gate and source.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A quadratic behavior is not observed in modern devices, for example, at the 65 nm technology node.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For low noise at narrow bandwidth, the higher input resistance of the FET is advantageous.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] FETs are divided into two families: *junction FET* (JFET) and *insulated gate FET* (IGFET).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The IGFET is more commonly known as a *metal–oxide–semiconductor FET* (MOSFET), reflecting its original construction from layers of metal (the gate), oxide (the insulation), and semiconductor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Unlike IGFETs, the JFET gate forms a p–n diode with the channel which lies between the source and drains.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Functionally, this makes the n-channel JFET the solid-state equivalent of the vacuum tube triode which, similarly, forms a diode between its grid and cathode.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Also, both devices operate in the *depletion-mode*, they both have a high input impedance, and they both conduct current under the control of an input voltage.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Metal–semiconductor FETs (MESFETs) are JFETs in which the reverse biased p–n junction is replaced by a metal–semiconductor junction.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] These, and the HEMTs (high-electron-mobility transistors, or HFETs), in which a two-dimensional electron gas with very high carrier mobility is used for charge transport, are especially suitable for use at very high frequencies (several GHz).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] FETs are further divided into *depletion-mode* and *enhancement-mode* types, depending on whether the channel is turned on or off with zero gate-to-source voltage.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For enhancement mode, the channel is off at zero bias, and a gate potential can *enhance* the conduction.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For the depletion mode, the channel is on at zero bias, and a gate potential (of the opposite polarity) can *deplete* the channel, reducing conduction.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For either mode, a more positive gate voltage corresponds to a higher current for n-channel devices and a lower current for p-channel devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Nearly all JFETs are depletion-mode because the diode junctions would forward bias and conduct if they were enhancement-mode devices, while most IGFETs are enhancement-mode types.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistor (MOSFET, MOS-FET, or MOS FET), also known as the metal–oxide–silicon transistor (MOS transistor, or MOS), is a type of field-effect transistor that is fabricated by the controlled oxidation of a semiconductor, typically silicon.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It has an insulated gate, whose voltage determines the conductivity of the device.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This ability to change conductivity with the amount of applied voltage can be used for amplifying or switching electronic signals.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The MOSFET is by far the most common transistor, and the basic building block of most modern electronics.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The MOSFET accounts for 99.9% of all transistors in the world.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Bipolar transistors are so named because they conduct by using both majority and minority carriers.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This construction produces two p–n junctions: a base–emitter junction and a base–collector junction, separated by a thin region of semiconductor known as the base region.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] BJTs have three terminals, corresponding to the three layers of semiconductor—an *emitter*, a *base*, and a *collector*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] They are useful in amplifiers because the currents at the emitter and collector are controllable by a relatively small base current.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because the base is narrow, most of these electrons will diffuse into the reverse-biased base–collector junction and be swept into the collector; perhaps one-hundredth of the electrons will recombine in the base, which is the dominant mechanism in the base current.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Since the base is doped lightly (in comparison to the emitter and collector regions), recombination rates are low, permitting more carriers to diffuse across the base region.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] By controlling the number of electrons that can leave the base, the number of electrons entering the collector can be controlled.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Collector current is approximately β (common-emitter current gain) times the base current.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] It is typically greater than 100 for small-signal transistors but can be smaller in transistors designed for high-power applications.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Unlike the field-effect transistor (see below), the BJT is a low-input-impedance device.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Also, as the base–emitter voltage (*V*BE) is increased, the base–emitter current and hence the collector–emitter current (*I*CE) increase exponentially according to the Shockley diode model and the Ebers–Moll model.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Because of this exponential relationship, the BJT has a higher transconductance than the FET.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Bipolar transistors can be made to conduct by exposure to light because the absorption of photons in the base region generates a photocurrent that acts as a base current; the collector current is approximately β times the photocurrent.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Devices designed for this purpose have a transparent window in the package and are called phototransistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The MOSFET is by far the most widely used transistor for both digital circuits as well as analog circuits, accounting for 99.9% of all transistors in the world.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The bipolar junction transistor (BJT) was previously the most commonly used transistor during the 1950s to 1960s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In integrated circuits, the desirable properties of MOSFETs allowed them to capture nearly all market share for digital circuits in the 1970s.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Discrete MOSFETs (typically power MOSFETs) can be applied in transistor applications, including analog circuits, voltage regulators, amplifiers, power transmitters, and motor drivers.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Three major identification standards are used for designating transistor devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In each, the alphanumeric prefix provides clues to the type of the device.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The JEDEC part numbering scheme evolved in the 1960s in the United States.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The JEDEC *EIA-370* transistor device numbers usually start with *2N*, indicating a three-terminal device.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Dual-gate field-effect transistors are four-terminal devices, and begin with 3N.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The prefix is followed by a two-, three- or four-digit number with no significance as to device properties, although early devices with low numbers tend to be germanium devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For example, 2N3055 is a silicon n–p–n power transistor, 2N1301 is a p–n–p germanium switching transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A letter suffix, such as A, is sometimes used to indicate a newer variant, but rarely gain groupings.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] In Japan, the JIS semiconductor designation (|JIS-C-7012), labels transistor devices starting with *2S*, e.g., 2SD965, but sometimes the 2S prefix is not marked on the package–a 2SD965 might only be marked *D965* and a 2SC1815 might be listed by a supplier as simply *C1815*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This series sometimes has suffixes, such as R, O, BL, standing for red, orange, blue, etc., to denote variants, such as tighter *h*FE (gain) groupings.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] The European Electronic Component Manufacturers Association (EECA) uses a numbering scheme that was inherited from Pro Electron when it merged with EECA in 1983.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] This scheme begins with two letters: the first gives the semiconductor type (A for germanium, B for silicon, and C for materials like GaAs); the second letter denotes the intended use (A for diode, C for general-purpose transistor, etc.).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] A three-digit sequence number (or one letter and two digits, for industrial types) follows.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] With early devices this indicated the case type.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Suffixes may be used, with a letter (e.g.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] C often means high *h*FE, such as in: BC549C) or other codes may follow to show gain (e.g.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Manufacturers of devices may have their proprietary numbering system, for example CK722.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Since devices are second-sourced, a manufacturer's prefix (like MPF in MPF102, which originally would denote a Motorola FET) now is an unreliable indicator of who made the device.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Some proprietary naming schemes adopt parts of other naming schemes, for example, a PN2222A is a (possibly Fairchild Semiconductor) 2N2222A in a plastic case (but a PN108 is a plastic version of a BC108, not a 2N108, while the PN100 is unrelated to other xx100 devices).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Military part numbers sometimes are assigned their codes, such as the British Military CV Naming System.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] Manufacturers buying large numbers of similar parts may have them supplied with *house numbers*, identifying a particular purchasing specification and not necessarily a device with a standardized registered number.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] With so many independent naming schemes, and the abbreviation of part numbers when printed on the devices, ambiguity sometimes occurs.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] For example, two different devices may be marked J176 (one the J176 low-power JFET, the other the higher-powered MOSFET 2SJ176).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] As older through-hole transistors are given surface-mount packaged counterparts, they tend to be assigned many different part numbers because manufacturers have their systems to cope with the variety in pinout arrangements and options for dual or matched n–p–n + p–n–p devices in one pack.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p01] So even when the original device (such as a 2N3904) may have been assigned by a standards authority, and well known by engineers over the years, the new versions are far from standardized in their naming.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The first BJTs were made from germanium (Ge).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Silicon (Si) types currently predominate but certain advanced microwave and high-performance versions now employ the *compound semiconductor* material gallium arsenide (GaAs) and the *semiconductor alloy* silicon–germanium (SiGe).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Single-element semiconductor material (Ge and Si) is described as *elemental*.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Rough parameters for the most common semiconductor materials used to make transistors are given in the adjacent table.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] These parameters will vary with an increase in temperature, electric field, impurity level, strain, and sundry other factors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The *junction forward voltage* is the voltage applied to the emitter-base junction of a BJT to make the base conduct a specified current.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The current increases exponentially as the junction forward voltage is increased.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The values given in the table are typical for a current of 1 mA (the same values apply to semiconductor diodes).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The lower the junction forward voltage the better, as this means that less power is required to drive the transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The junction forward voltage for a given current decreases with an increase in temperature.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] For a typical silicon junction, the change is −2.1 mV/°C.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] In some circuits special compensating elements (sensistors) must be used to compensate for such changes.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The density of mobile carriers in the channel of a MOSFET is a function of the electric field forming the channel and of various other phenomena such as the impurity level in the channel.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Some impurities, called dopants, are introduced deliberately in making a MOSFET, to control the MOSFET electrical behavior.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The *electron mobility* and *hole mobility* columns show the average speed that electrons and holes diffuse through the semiconductor material with an electric field of 1 volt per meter applied across the material.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] In general, the higher the electron mobility the faster the transistor can operate.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The table indicates that Ge is a better material than Si in this respect.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] It is less suitable for fabricating integrated circuits.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Because the electron mobility is higher than the hole mobility for all semiconductor materials, a given bipolar n–p–n transistor tends to be swifter than an equivalent p–n–p transistor.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] GaAs has the highest electron mobility of the three semiconductors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] It is for this reason that GaAs is used in high-frequency applications.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] A relatively recent FET development, the *high-electron-mobility transistor* (HEMT), has a heterostructure (junction between different semiconductor materials) of aluminium gallium arsenide (AlGaAs)-gallium arsenide (GaAs) which has twice the electron mobility of a GaAs-metal barrier junction.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Because of their high speed and low noise, HEMTs are used in satellite receivers working at frequencies around 12 GHz.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] HEMTs based on gallium nitride and aluminum gallium nitride (AlGaN/GaN HEMTs) provide still higher electron mobility and are being developed for various applications.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Maximum junction temperature values represent a cross-section taken from various manufacturers' datasheets.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] This temperature should not be exceeded or the transistor may be damaged.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Discrete transistors can be individually packaged transistors or unpackaged transistor chips.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Transistors come in many different semiconductor packages (see image).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The two main categories are *through-hole* (or *leaded*), and *surface-mount*, also known as *surface-mount device* (SMD).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The *ball grid array* (BGA) is the latest surface-mount package.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] It has solder balls on the underside in place of leads.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Because they are smaller and have shorter interconnections, SMDs have better high-frequency characteristics but lower power ratings.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Transistor packages are made of glass, metal, ceramic, or plastic.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The package often dictates the power rating and frequency characteristics.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Power transistors have larger packages that can be clamped to heat sinks for enhanced cooling.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Additionally, most power transistors have the collector or drain physically connected to the metal enclosure.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] At the other extreme, some surface-mount *microwave* transistors are as small as grains of sand.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Often a given transistor type is available in several packages.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Transistor packages are mainly standardized, but the assignment of a transistor's functions to the terminals is not: other transistor types can assign other functions to the package's terminals.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Even for the same transistor type the terminal assignment can vary (normally indicated by a suffix letter to the part number, q.e.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Nowadays most transistors come in a wide range of SMT packages.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] In comparison, the list of available through-hole packages is relatively small.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Here is a short list of the most common through-hole transistors packages in alphabetical order: ATV, E-line, MRT, HRT, SC-43, SC-72, TO-3, TO-18, TO-39, TO-92, TO-126, TO220, TO247, TO251, TO262, ZTX851.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Unpackaged transistor chips (die) may be assembled into hybrid devices.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] The IBM SLT module of the 1960s is one example of such a hybrid circuit module using glass passivated transistor (and diode) die.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Other packaging techniques for discrete transistors as chips include *direct chip attach* (DCA) and *chip-on-board* (COB).
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Researchers have made several kinds of flexible transistors, including organic field-effect transistors.
[src:transistor-scaling/transistor-p02] Flexible transistors are useful in some kinds of flexible displays and other flexible electronics.
